2000 Internally Displaced Persons (IDPs) in Kuchigoro, Abuja on Sunday benefited from the Nigerian Navy medical outreach programme. 

The medical rhapsody and free community medical services, which was part of activities to commemorate the Navy's 62nd Anniversary, saw IDPs in Kuchingoro Camp, Abuja, benefiting from different services such as blood pressure checks, eye examination, issuance of free eye glasses where necessary as well as de-worming of children and adults. 

Speaking at the event, the Chief of Naval Staff, Vice Admiral Ibok Ete-Ibas, said the event was part of the efforts of the service to enhance healthy civil-military relationship and the Navy's corporate social responsibility. 

Ete-Ibas, who was represented by Captain Abdulazeez Zubairu, said the Nigerian Navy was concerned about the plight of the the IDPs, having left their comfort zones as a result of crises. 

HeÂ  that the Armed Forces of Nigeria was winning the war against Boko Haram terrorists and assured that the IDPs would soon return to their various homes as the war areas will soon be conducive for their return.